rom scholars based in Bahrain, Canada, Egypt France, the UK and the USAThis book demonstrates the advantage of a corpus based approach to Arabic, and presents an overview of current research on the Arabic language within corpus linguistics. Dealing not only with modern standard Arabic, the book also considers classical and colloquial forms.With a range of international contributors presenting their experience of working with Arabic from a particular perspective, the book includes chapters on corpus building, the tools needed to explore the Arabic language, the use of corpora to explore the grammar of Arabic, and the study of discourse in Arabic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Arabic.2bisacsh1 aAbdulrahim, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlsaif, Amal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtwell, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardie, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHardie, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Wesam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarkert, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcEnery, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeil, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohamed, Ghada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParkinson, Dilworth B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSartori, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYounis, Nagwa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYounis,